  "prompt": "In what grade do American students learn topics like integral, derivatives, organic chemistry, and waves in detail?",
  "response": "In the United States, the topics you mentioned are typically covered in different educational contexts:\n\n1. **Calculus (Integral and Derivatives)**: \n   - Students generally study calculus in high school, often in grades 11 or 12, typically in an Advanced Placement (AP) Calculus course. Some students may also take calculus courses in college.\n\n2. **Organic Chemistry**: \n   - Organic chemistry is usually introduced at the college level, often as part of a two-semester sequence in a university-level chemistry curriculum. Some high school programs may offer it as part of an advanced science track, but this is less common.\n\n3. **Waves (Physics)**: \n   - The study of waves is typically covered in high school physics courses, often taken in grades 11 or 12. It may also be revisited in more detail in college-level physics courses.\n\nIn summary, calculus (including integrals and derivatives) is usually studied in high school, while organic chemistry is mainly a college-level subject, and waves are covered in high school physics classes.",
